06586nam a22009255i 9789812308221DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092009si     fo  d z      eng d  a2009323612  a97898123082217 a10.1355/97898123082212doi  a(DE-B1597)492442  a(OCoLC)1042031348  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG00aHQ1031b.M85 2009 7aSOC0390002bisacsh00aMuslim-Non-Muslim Marriage :bPolitical and Cultural Contestations in Southeast Asia /ced. by Gavin W. Jones, Chee Heng Leng, Maznah Mohamad. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (340 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tTHE CONTRIBUTORS -- tGLOSSARY -- tChapter 1. MUSLIM-NON-MUSLIM MARRIAGE, RIGHTS AND THE STATE IN SOUTHEAST ASIA -- tSECTION I. POLITICAL AND LEGAL CONTESTATIONS -- tChapter 2. TRAPPED BETWEEN LEGAL UNIFICATION AND PLURALISM -- tChapter 3. PRIVATE LIVES, PUBLIC CONTENTION -- tChapter 4. LEGAL ASPECTS OF MUSLIMNON- MUSLIM MARRIAGE IN INDONESIA -- tChapter 5. THE POLITICO-RELIGIOUS CONTESTATION -- tSECTION II. LIVED REALITIES -- tChapter 6. “NOT MUSLIM, NOT MINANGKABAU” -- tChapter 7. KHAO KHAEK -- tChapter 8. INTERETHNIC MARRIAGES AND CONVERSION TO ISLAM IN KOTA BHARU -- tSECTION III. PERSPECTIVES -- tChapter 9. PROMOTING GENDER EQUITY THROUGH INTERRELIGIOUS MARRIAGE -- tChapter 10. MUSLIM-NON-MUSLIM MARRIAGE IN SINGAPORE -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"This is an excellent and rare exploration of a sensitive religious issue from many perspectives – legal, cultural and political. The case studies from Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Thailand portray the important and exciting, yet very difficult, negotiation of Islamic teachings in the changing realities of Southeast Asia, home to the majority of Muslims in the world. Interreligious marriage is an important indicator of good relations between communities in religiously diverse countries. This book will also be of great interest to students and scholars of religious pluralism in a Southeast Asian context, which has not been studied adequately." - Zainal Abidin Bagir, Executive Director, Center for Religious and Cross-cultural Studies (CRCS), Gadjah Mada University, Indonesia "The issue of Muslim-non-Muslim marriages has different connotations in the different Southeast Asian states. For example, in Thailand it is more a fluid cultural issue but in Malaysia it reflects great racial schisms with severe legal implications. This book is a welcome one as it examines the issue not only from the perspectives of various Southeast Asian nations but also from so many angles; the legal, historical, social, cultural, anthropological and philosophical. The work is scholarly, yet accessible. Underlying it, there is a vital streak of humanism." - Azmi Sharom, Associate Professor, Faculty of Law, University of Malaya  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInterfaith marriagezSoutheast Asia. 0aMarriage lawzSoutheast Asia. 0aMarriagexReligious aspectsxIslam. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh1 aAziz, Zarizana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCammack, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCholil, Suhadi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElfira, Mina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGavin W. Jones, , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeng Leng, Chee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJones, Gavin W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeng, Chee Heng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.